[{"id":"/sicp/2.2.1","tag":"TITLE","body":"2.2.1  \n    Representing Sequences"},{"tag":"TEXT","id":"#p1","child":[{"body":"\n\n    One of the useful structures we can build with pairs is a \n    ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"EM","child":[{"body":"sequence","tag":"#text"}]},{"body":"—an ordered collection of data objects.  There\n    are, of course, many ways to represent sequences in terms of pairs.  One\n    particularly straightforward representation is illustrated in\n    figure ,\n    where the sequence 1, 2, 3, 4 is represented as a chain of pairs.  The\n    ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"SCHEMEINLINE","body":"car"},{"body":"\n    of each pair is the\n    corresponding item in the chain, and the\n    ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"SCHEMEINLINE","body":"cdr"},{"body":"\n    of the pair is the next pair in the chain.  The\n    ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"SCHEMEINLINE","body":"cdr"},{"body":"\n    of the final pair signals the end of the\n    \n\tsequence by pointing to a\n\tdistinguished value that is not a pair,\n      \n    represented in box-and-pointer\n    diagrams as a diagonal line\n    \n    and in programs as\n    the value of the variable ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"SCHEMEINLINE","body":"nil"},{"body":".\n    The entire sequence is constructed by nested\n    ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"SCHEMEINLINE","body":"cons"},{"body":"\n    operations:\n    ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"SNIPPET","latex":false,"id":1,"eval":true,"prependLength":0,"program":"chap=2&prgrm=NwAgygkgwgCiBMA6JBGAUGgFAYwPYDsBnEdEM8nA4+Ncu+yokAZlvvfceIBYR8BLADYBKUcKA","body":"(cons 1\n      (cons 2\n            (cons 3\n                  (cons 4 nil)))) "}]},{"tag":"FIGURE","scale":"70%","src":"img_original/ch2-Z-G-13.svg","id":"#fig-","captionHref":"","captionName":"Figure  ","captionBody":[{"body":"The sequence 1, 2, 3, 4 represented as a chain of pairs.\n\t  ","tag":"#text"}]},{"tag":"TEXT","id":"#p2","child":[{"body":"\n    Such a sequence of pairs, formed by nested\n    ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"SCHEMEINLINE","body":"cons"},{"body":"es,\n      \n    is called a\n    ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"EM","child":[{"body":"list","tag":"#text"}]},{"body":", and\n    Scheme\n    provides a primitive called \n    ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"SCHEMEINLINE","body":"list"},{"body":" to help in constructing \n    lists.","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"FOOTNOTE_REF","id":"#footnote-link-1","body":"1","href":"/sicp/2.2.1#footnote-1"},{"body":"\n    The above sequence could be produced by\n    ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"SCHEMEINLINE","body":"(list 1 2 3 4)"},{"body":".\n    In general, \n    ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"SNIPPET","latex":true,"eval":false,"body":"\n(list a$_{1}$ a$_{2}$ $\\ldots$ a$_{n}$)\n      "},{"body":"\n    is equivalent to\n    ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"SNIPPET","latex":true,"eval":false,"body":"\n(cons a$_{1}$ (cons a$_{2}$ (cons $\\ldots$ (cons a$_{n}$ nil) $\\ldots$)))\n      "},{"body":"\n        Lisp systems conventionally print lists by printing the sequence of\n        elements, enclosed in parentheses.  Thus, the data object in\n        figure \n\tis printed as\n\t","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"SCHEMEINLINE","body":"(1 2 3 4)"},{"body":":\n      ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"SNIPPET","latex":false,"id":2,"eval":true,"prependLength":0,"program":"chap=2&prgrm=NwAgygkgwgCiBMA6JBGAUGgFAEwKYDMBLAO1xAHtSBaAFwAsAncgVwHM6r8WGRMAbQgGcaIFAhABmEABYAlLIyVctRi3aduQA","body":"(define one-through-four (list 1 2 3 4)) "},{"tag":"SNIPPET","latex":false,"id":3,"eval":true,"prependLength":3,"program":"chap=2&prgrm=NwAgygkgwgCiBMA6JBGAUGgFAEwKYDMBLAO1xAHtSBaAFwAsAncgVwHM6r8WGRMAbQgGcaIFAhABmEABYAlLIyVctRi3aduQA","body":"one-through-four ","output":"(1 2 3 4)"},{"body":"\n        Be careful not to confuse the expression\n\t","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"SCHEMEINLINE","body":"(list 1 2 3 4)"},{"body":" with the list\n\t","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"SCHEMEINLINE","body":"(1 2 3 4)"},{"body":", which is the result obtained\n\twhen the expression is evaluated.  Attempting to evaluate the\n\texpression ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"SCHEMEINLINE","body":"(1 2 3 4)"},{"body":" will signal an error\n\twhen the interpreter tries to apply the procedure\n        ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"SCHEMEINLINE","body":"1"},{"body":" to arguments \n        ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"SCHEMEINLINE","body":"2"},{"body":", ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"SCHEMEINLINE","body":"3"},{"body":", \n        and ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"SCHEMEINLINE","body":"4"},{"body":".\n    ","tag":"#text"}]},{"tag":"TEXT","id":"#p3","child":[{"body":"\n    We can think of \n    ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"SCHEMEINLINE","body":"car"},{"body":"\n    as selecting the first item in the list, and of \n    ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"SCHEMEINLINE","body":"cdr"},{"body":"\n    as selecting the sublist consisting of all but the first item.  Nested\n    applications of\n    ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"SCHEMEINLINE","body":"car"},{"body":"\n    and\n    ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"SCHEMEINLINE","body":"cdr"},{"body":"\n    can be used to extract the second, third, and subsequent items in the\n    list.","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"FOOTNOTE_REF","id":"#footnote-link-2","body":"2","href":"/sicp/2.2.1#footnote-2"},{"body":"\n    The constructor \n    ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"SCHEMEINLINE","body":"cons"},{"body":"\n    makes a list like the original one, but with an additional item at the\n    beginning.\n    ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"SNIPPET","latex":false,"id":4,"eval":true,"prependLength":3,"program":"chap=2&prgrm=NwAgygkgwgCiBMA6JBGAUGgFAEwKYDMBLAO1xAHtSBaAFwAsAncgVwHM6r8WGRMAbQgGcaIFAhABmEABYAlLIyYAxgEMelXLUYt2nbrKA","body":"(car one-through-four) ","output":"1"},{"tag":"SNIPPET","latex":false,"id":5,"eval":true,"prependLength":3,"program":"chap=2&prgrm=NwAgygkgwgCiBMA6JBGAUGgFAEwKYDMBLAO1xAHtSBaAFwAsAncgVwHM6r8WGRMAbQgGcaIFAhABmEABYAlLIyYAxth6VctRi3adusoA","body":"(cdr one-through-four) ","output":"(2 3 4)"},{"tag":"SNIPPET","latex":false,"id":6,"eval":true,"prependLength":3,"program":"chap=2&prgrm=NwAgygkgwgCiBMA6JBGAUGgFAEwKYDMBLAO1xAHtSBaAFwAsAncgVwHM6r8WGRMAbQgGcaIFAhABmEABYAlLIyYAxgEMey7D0q5ajFu07d5QA","body":"(car (cdr one-through-four)) ","output":"2"},{"tag":"SNIPPET","latex":false,"id":7,"eval":true,"prependLength":3,"program":"chap=2&prgrm=NwAgygkgwgCiBMA6JBGAUGgFAEwKYDMBLAO1xAHtSBaAFwAsAncgVwHM6r8WGRMAbQgGcaIFAhABmEABYAlLIyYAxpUGiADBWr0mbDl2YNZQA","body":"(cons 10 one-through-four) ","output":"(10 1 2 3 4)"},{"tag":"SNIPPET","latex":false,"id":8,"eval":true,"prependLength":3,"program":"chap=2&prgrm=NwAgygkgwgCiBMA6JBGAUGgFAEwKYDMBLAO1xAHtSBaAFwAsAncgVwHM6r8WGRMAbQgGcaIFAhABmEABYAlLIyYAxpUEgArBWr0mbDl2YNZQA","body":"(cons 5 one-through-four) ","output":"(5 1 2 3 4)"},{"body":"\n        The value of ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"SCHEMEINLINE","body":"nil"},{"body":", used to terminate the\n\tchain of pairs, can be thought of as a sequence of no elements, the \n        ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"EM","child":[{"body":"empty list","tag":"#text"}]},{"body":".  The word ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"EM","child":[{"body":"nil","tag":"#text"}]},{"body":" is a contraction of the\n\tLatin word ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"EM","child":[{"body":"nihil","tag":"#text"}]},{"body":", which means\n\t\"","tag":"#text"},{"body":"nothing.","tag":"#text"},{"body":"\"","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"FOOTNOTE_REF","id":"#footnote-link-3","body":"3","href":"/sicp/2.2.1#footnote-3"}]},{"tag":"SUBHEADING","id":"#h1","child":[{"body":"List operations","tag":"#text"}]},{"tag":"TEXT","id":"#p4","child":[{"body":"\n    The use of pairs to represent sequences of elements as lists is accompanied\n    by conventional programming techniques for manipulating lists by\n    successively \n    \"","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"SCHEMEINLINE","body":"cdr"},{"body":"ing down","tag":"#text"},{"body":"\"\n\tthe lists.\n      \n    For example, the\n    procedure","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"SCHEMEINLINE","body":"list-ref"},{"body":"\n    takes as arguments a list and a number ","tag":"#text"},{"body":"$n$","tag":"LATEX"},{"body":" and\n    returns the ","tag":"#text"},{"body":"$n$","tag":"LATEX"},{"body":"th item of the list.  It is\n    customary to number the elements of the list beginning with 0.  The method\n    for computing\n    ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"SCHEMEINLINE","body":"list-ref"},{"body":"\n    is the following:\n    ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"UL","child":[{"tag":"LI","child":[{"body":"\n\tFor ","tag":"#text"},{"body":"$n=0$","tag":"LATEX"},{"body":",\n\t","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"SCHEMEINLINE","body":"list-ref"},{"body":"\n\tshould return the\n\t","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"SCHEMEINLINE","body":"car"},{"body":"\n\tof the list.\n      ","tag":"#text"}]},{"tag":"LI","child":[{"body":"\n\tOtherwise,\n\t","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"SCHEMEINLINE","body":"list-ref"},{"body":"\n\tshould return  the ","tag":"#text"},{"body":"$(n-1)$","tag":"LATEX"},{"body":"st item of the\n\t","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"SCHEMEINLINE","body":"cdr"},{"body":"\n\tof the list.\n      ","tag":"#text"}]}]},{"tag":"SNIPPET","latex":false,"id":9,"eval":true,"prependLength":0,"program":"chap=2&prgrm=NwAgygkgwgCiBMA6JBGAUGgFAEwKYDMBLAO1xEwBtCBnAFwFoAnAkQ23AW2pGIEo0Q5QvnIBeHiAAM-QbPIBjAIaNW7LjLnkqdJi0zzsKtp2q9y9CSl7X+WPEVIhqARwCuy3N0o1aIFCAAWEABOPwA2BABWayxtBmYRF3dmbgBmXiA","body":"(define (list-ref items n)\n  (if (= n 0)\n      (car items)\n      (list-ref (cdr items) (- n 1)))) "},{"tag":"SNIPPET","latex":false,"id":10,"eval":true,"prependLength":6,"program":"chap=2&prgrm=NwAgygkgwgCiBMA6JBGAUGgFAEwKYDMBLAO1xEwBtCBnAFwFoAnAkQ23AW2pGIEo0Q5QvnIBeHiAAM-QbPIBjAIaNW7LjLnkqdJi0zzsKtp2q9y9CSl7X+WPEVIhqARwCuy3N0o1aIFCAAWEABOPwA2BABWayxtBmYRF3dmbgBmXiA","body":"(define squares (list 1 4 9 16 25))\n(list-ref squares 3) ","output":"16"}]},{"tag":"TEXT","id":"#p5","child":[{"body":"\n    Often we\n    ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"SCHEMEINLINE","body":"cdr"},{"body":" down the whole list.\n      \n    To aid in this,\n    Scheme\n    includes a primitive\n    predicate\n    ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"SCHEMEINLINE","body":"null?"},{"body":",\n    which tests whether its argument is the empty list.  The\n    procedure","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"SCHEMEINLINE","body":"length"},{"body":", which returns the number of items in\n    a list, illustrates this typical pattern of use:\n    ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"SNIPPET","latex":false,"id":11,"eval":true,"prependLength":0,"program":"chap=2&prgrm=NwAgygkgwgCiBMA6JBGAUGgFAEwKYDMBLAO1xEwBtdiBzAFwAsRC7cBbAZwEo0RzD85YgFcKFAPzNWnHnzkgADL3nkA1CBTkqtRuQDG2AE5T23LuZ5Y8RUiAD22bBy2EOdDSADMIAKwgA7OZY2vRMDk5cQA","body":"(define (length items)\n  (if (null? items)\n      0\n      (+ 1 (length (cdr items))))) "},{"tag":"SNIPPET","latex":false,"id":12,"eval":true,"prependLength":0,"program":"chap=2&prgrm=NwAgygkgwgCiBMA6JBGAUGgFAEwKYDMBLAO1xAHttsBnETAG0OoBcQUQBmEAVhAHYAlAKz1cxAObMAFhSrUBQA","body":"(define odds (list 1 3 5 7))\n(length odds) "},{"body":"\n    The ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"SCHEMEINLINE","body":"length"},{"body":"procedure\n    implements a simple recursive plan. The reduction step is:\n    ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"UL","child":[{"tag":"LI","child":[{"body":"\n\tThe ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"SCHEMEINLINE","body":"length"},{"body":" of any list is 1 plus the\n\t","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"SCHEMEINLINE","body":"length"},{"body":" of the\n\t","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"SCHEMEINLINE","body":"cdr"},{"body":"\n\tof the list.\n      ","tag":"#text"}]}]},{"body":"\n    This is applied successively until we reach the base case:\n    ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"UL","child":[{"tag":"LI","child":[{"body":"\n\tThe ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"SCHEMEINLINE","body":"length"},{"body":" of the empty list is 0.\n      ","tag":"#text"}]}]},{"body":"\n    We could also compute ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"SCHEMEINLINE","body":"length"},{"body":" in an iterative\n    style:\n    ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"SNIPPET","latex":false,"id":13,"eval":true,"prependLength":0,"program":"chap=2&prgrm=NwAgygkgwgCiBMA6JBGAUGgFAEwKYDMBLAO1xEwBtdiBzAFwAsRC7cBbAZwEo0Ry8ipclVqMAtC1wAnEAEMQAYwD2AV2J0efPpkL5yxFRQoB+OZq0XlaurwtbK1egwmsZmBdhmyu5ANQgURVV1LlDzB1FnSRlJThAABlCMHAISMiVsbA5hQg46AJAAZhAAVhAAdiSIpxAMrK4gA","body":"(define (length items)\n  (define (length-iter a count)\n    (if (null? a)\n        count\n        (length-iter (cdr a) (+ 1 count))))\n  (length-iter items 0)) "}]},{"tag":"TEXT","id":"#p6","child":[{"body":"\n    Another conventional programming technique is to \n    \"","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"SCHEMEINLINE","body":"cons"},{"body":" up","tag":"#text"},{"body":"\"\n\tthe heads and tails of an answer list while\n      ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"SCHEMEINLINE","body":"cdr"},{"body":"ing down a list,\n      \n    as in the\n    procedure","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"SCHEMEINLINE","body":"append"},{"body":", which takes two lists as arguments and\n    combines their elements to make a new list:\n    ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"SNIPPET","latex":false,"id":14,"eval":true,"prependLength":10,"program":"chap=2&prgrm=NwAgygkgwgCiBMA6JBGAUGgFAEwKYDMBLAO1xEwEMAHK3Y7EAG0IGcAXFJ1t+ASjRDlC+csQCujRgH4u7FP0GLZPAUvIBjAPbEWGigCdl88tVr0N2Q8zm9lfXg4w4CJMiwCOYg7l2ZrbEE4AFhAATkCANgQAVkcsPCJSEE1sbF9-QJAAZhBokAB2OMoaOgYPL30fZNSWXiA","body":"(append squares odds) ","output":"(1 4 9 16 25 1 3 5 7)"},{"tag":"SNIPPET","latex":false,"id":15,"eval":true,"prependLength":10,"program":"chap=2&prgrm=NwAgygkgwgCiBMA6JBGAUGgFAEwKYDMBLAO1xEwEMAHK3Y7EAG0IGcAXFJ1t+ASjRDlC+csQCujRgH4u7FP0GLZPAUvIBjAPbEWGigCdl88tVr0N2Q8zm9lfXg4w4CJMiwCOYg7l2ZrbEE4AFhAATkCANgQAVkcsPCJSEE1sbF9-QJAAZhBokAB2OMoaOgYUtJAPL30fXiA","body":"(append odds squares) ","output":"(1 3 5 7 1 4 9 16 25)"},{"tag":"SCHEMEINLINE","body":"Append"},{"body":"\n    is also implemented using a recursive plan. To\n    ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"SCHEMEINLINE","body":"append"},{"body":" lists\n    ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"SCHEMEINLINE","body":"list1"},{"body":" and ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"SCHEMEINLINE","body":"list2"},{"body":",\n    do the following:\n    ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"UL","child":[{"tag":"LI","child":[{"body":"\n\tIf ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"SCHEMEINLINE","body":"list1"},{"body":" is the empty list, then the\n      result is just ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"SCHEMEINLINE","body":"list2"},{"body":".\n      ","tag":"#text"}]},{"tag":"LI","child":[{"body":"\n\tOtherwise, ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"SCHEMEINLINE","body":"append"},{"body":" the\n\t","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"SCHEMEINLINE","body":"cdr"},{"body":"\n\tof ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"SCHEMEINLINE","body":"list1"},{"body":" and \n\t","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"SCHEMEINLINE","body":"list2"},{"body":", and\n\t","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"SCHEMEINLINE","body":"cons"},{"body":"\n\tthe\n\t","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"SCHEMEINLINE","body":"car"},{"body":"\n\tof ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"SCHEMEINLINE","body":"list1"},{"body":"\n\t    onto the result:\n\t  ","tag":"#text"}]}]},{"tag":"SNIPPET","latex":false,"id":16,"eval":true,"prependLength":5,"program":"chap=2&prgrm=NwAgygkgwgCiBMA6JBGAUGgFAEwKYDMBLAO1xAGcBHAVwEMAnXckTAG0PIBcQUQAWEAE4eANgQBWAJSSMOAiTIB7bNmZsO3XgGYQ4kAHZpsvEVItaABwu5i2EOy68HneDJAtC+FsWqtWAfnsNFDd3MOd4NDCwzABjRWI1WIYgx0lzKxs7OOx6VM4Q-NdpGSxLa1sKGgYmEGVVSSA","body":"(define (append list1 list2)\n  (if (null? list1)\n      list2\n      (cons (car list1) (append (cdr list1) list2)))) "}]},{"tag":"EXERCISE","title":"Exercise 2.17","id":"#ex-2.17","child":[{"body":" \n    Define a\n    procedure","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"SCHEMEINLINE","body":"last-pair"},{"body":"\n    that returns the list that contains only the last element of a given\n    (nonempty) list:\n    ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"SNIPPET","latex":false,"id":17,"eval":true,"prependLength":3,"program":"chap=2&prgrm=NwAgygkgwgCiBMA6JBGAUG4oA2BDAzgC4C0ADrgJYBOIhA9iAEYCmIA5hQG7MB2TAniCIBXACa9CGABR4iZSjRkUiCAMwgA7PBAoALAE4Qq3QEoTQA","body":"(last-pair (list 23 72 149 34)) ","output":"(34)"}],"solution":[{"tag":"SNIPPET","latex":false,"id":18,"eval":true,"prependLength":3,"program":"chap=2&prgrm=NwAgygkgwgCiBMA6JBGAUG4oA2BDAzgC4C0ADrgJYBOIhA9iAEYCmIA5hQG7MB2TAniCIBXACa9CGDAAo8RMpRqyKRBAGYQAdnggUAFgCcINXoCUpoA","body":" "}]},{"tag":"EXERCISE","title":"Exercise 2.18","id":"#ex-2.18","child":[{"body":"\n    Define a\n    procedure","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"SCHEMEINLINE","body":"reverse"},{"body":" that takes a list as argument and\n    returns a list of the same elements in reverse order:\n    ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"SNIPPET","latex":false,"id":19,"eval":true,"prependLength":0,"program":"chap=2&prgrm=NwAgygkgwgCiBMA6JBGAUGgFAJwKYDddsBnXETAGwEtiAXEFEAFhAE4GA2BAVgEpegA","body":"(reverse (list 1 4 9 16 25)) ","output":"(25 16 9 4 1)"}],"solution":[{"body":"\n      Naive reverse (what is the run time?):\n      ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"SNIPPET","latex":false,"id":20,"eval":false},{"body":"\n      A better version:\n      ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"SNIPPET","latex":false,"id":21,"eval":false}]},{"tag":"EXERCISE","title":"Exercise 2.19","id":"#ex-2.19","child":[{"body":"\n      Consider the \n      \n      change-counting program of\n      section ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"REF","body":"1.2.2","href":"/sicp/1.2.2"},{"body":".  It would be nice to be\n      able to easily change the currency used by the program, so that we could\n      compute the number of ways to change a British pound, for example.  As\n      the program is written, the knowledge of the currency is distributed\n      partly into the\n      procedure","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"SCHEMEINLINE","body":"first-denomination"},{"body":"\n      and partly into the\n      procedure","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"SCHEMEINLINE","body":"count-change"},{"body":"\n      (which knows\n      that there are five kinds of U.S. coins).\n      It would be nicer\n      to be able to supply a list of coins to be used for making change.\n    ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"TEXT","id":"#p7","child":[{"body":"\n      We want to rewrite the\n      procedure","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"SCHEMEINLINE","body":"cc"},{"body":" so that its second argument is a list of\n      the values of the coins to use rather than an integer specifying which\n      coins to use.  We could then have lists that defined each kind of\n      currency:\n      ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"SNIPPET","latex":false,"id":22,"eval":true,"prependLength":0,"program":"chap=2&prgrm=NwAgygkgwgCiBMA6JBGAUGgFAEwKYDMBLAO1xAFcBnAWgGMB7EykTAG0MoBcQBWABgQ8QKAUJQBKcRhwESZcgGs6jYszYduI0QPgCRvBMMlA","body":"(define us-coins (list 50 25 10 5 1))\n\n(define uk-coins (list 100 50 20 10 5 2 1)) "},{"body":"\n      We could then call ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"SCHEMEINLINE","body":"cc"},{"body":" as follows:\n      ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"SNIPPET","latex":false,"id":23,"eval":true,"prependLength":18,"program":"chap=2&prgrm=NwAgygkgwgCiBMA6JBGAUG4oBmBLATgM4AuAtACYCmAdgPYC2u1AhsbrdQDQiUAeAxpQAOZPETJU6jFmw6ZQzauRB1S9WvkoB+EMVogARpRABzXADcahgJ4gSAV0nEMACip5qxl-34hm6+2piEH5aJlJzZgAbe0pCAEo0EBBvDmUXFwBePwCgkAAGeJAUROSysoyNFIAeHNpA4MKU1XVNHVDwyJi4+KLCpPKKyijCSgHB5JcAahSfOobxiaWXPkERUjESChoGJlZ2ahCw6gjo2ITSpfLvXxdSeaDFq+XNiR3pfY4jzrOey+fBh0Tl1zr0wa53ExjPZCKQgYQUlFcCQQABWfIIVHFDFYkqJNBuSgeaEAazhxwRLiRKJQ+RxGPgGNpaIQxV6rjmtIxMPJTASQA","body":"(cc 100 us-coins) ","output":"292"},{"body":"\n      To do this will require changing the program\n      ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"SCHEMEINLINE","body":"cc"},{"body":" somewhat.  It will still have the same\n      form, but it will access its second argument differently, as follows:\n      ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"SNIPPET","latex":false,"id":24,"eval":true,"prependLength":8,"program":"chap=2&prgrm=NwAgygkgwgCiBMA6JBGAUG4oBmBLATgM4AuAtACYCmAdgPYC2u1AhsbrdQDQiUAeAxpQAOZPETJU6jFmw6ZQzauRB1S9WvkoB+EMVogARpRABzXADcahgJ4gSAV0nEMACip5qx+4VL9aTQhAXABtcEhAAVgAGBAiQFBi4lABKZNd3Ji8Aa19-akCQsOJ4qMSY+BiEyIR41PTKD2MXfn4QZnV7amK-JlJzZmD7SkI0kCC-JSCXAF42jq6QKOTatDG1tZcXDSCAHjnaTuKloNV1TR0e6j6BoZHlpdX1jcpgwkpHp7GXAGpx1vaDl0Pp8QS4+IIRKQxCQKDQGExWOxqCBLtdBsM6iCns1Wi5SPtDsCsaDoRI4dJERwUXk0bdMcTPqj+ui7qk0mgcSUYt5cgFkkA","body":"(define (cc amount coin-values)\n  (cond ((= amount 0) 1)\n        ((or (< amount 0) (no-more? coin-values)) 0)\n        (else\n         (+ (cc amount\n                (except-first-denomination coin-values))\n            (cc (- amount\n                   (first-denomination coin-values))\n                coin-values))))) "},{"body":"\n      Define the\n      procedures","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"SCHEMEINLINE","body":"first-denomination"},{"body":",","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"SCHEMEINLINE","body":"except-first-denomination"},{"body":",\n      and\n      ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"SCHEMEINLINE","body":"no-more?"},{"body":"\n      in terms of primitive operations on list structures.  Does the order of\n      the list\n      ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"SCHEMEINLINE","body":"coin-values"},{"body":"\n      affect the answer produced by ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"SCHEMEINLINE","body":"cc"},{"body":"?\n      Why or why not?\n    ","tag":"#text"}]}],"solution":[{"tag":"SNIPPET","latex":false,"id":25,"eval":true,"prependLength":18,"program":"chap=2&prgrm=NwAgygkgwgCiBMA6JBGAUG4oBmBLATgM4AuAtACYCmAdgPYC2u1AhsbrdQDQiUAeAxpQAOZPETJU6jFmw6ZQzauRB1S9WvkoB+EMVogARpRABzXADcahgJ4gSAV0nEMACip5qxl-34hm6+2piEH5aJlJzZgAbe0pCAEo0EBBvDmUXFwBePwCgkAAGeJAUROSysoyNFIAeHNpA4MKU1XVNHVDwyJi4+KLCpPKKyijCSgHB5JcAahSfOobxiaWXPkERUjESChoGJlZ2ahCw6gjo2ITSpfLvXxdSeaDFq+XNiR3pfY4jzrOey+fBh0Tl1zr0wa53ExjPZCKQgYQUlFcCQQABWfIIVHFDFYkqJNBuSgeaEAazhxwRLiRKJQ+RxGPgGNpaIQxV6GFcc1pGJh5KYCSAA","body":" "},{"body":"\n      The order of the list ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"SCHEMEINLINE","body":"coin_values"},{"body":"\n      does not affect the answer given by any correct solution of the problem,\n      because the given list represents an unordered collection of\n      denominations.\n    ","tag":"#text"}]},{"tag":"EXERCISE","title":"Exercise 2.20","id":"#ex-2.20","child":[{"body":"\n        The procedures\n        ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"SCHEMEINLINE","body":"+"},{"body":", ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"SCHEMEINLINE","body":"*"},{"body":", and\n\t","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"SCHEMEINLINE","body":"list"},{"body":" take arbitrary numbers of arguments.\n\tOne way to define such procedures is to use\n\t","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"SCHEMEINLINE","body":"define"},{"body":" with ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"EM","child":[{"body":"dotted-tail notation","tag":"#text"}]},{"body":".\n\tIn a procedure definition, a parameter list that has a dot before the\n\tlast parameter name indicates that, when the procedure is called, the\n\tinitial parameters (if any) will have as values the initial arguments, \n        as usual, but the final parameter's value will be a ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"EM","child":[{"body":"list","tag":"#text"}]},{"body":"\n\tof any remaining arguments. For instance, given the definition\n        ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"SNIPPET","latex":false,"id":26,"eval":true,"prependLength":0,"program":"chap=2&prgrm=NwAgygkgwgCiBMA6JBGAUGgFAEwKYDMBLAO1xE3xAA8QBPEREALwEoQASAHQBsBDYgObcynAC64qowqIDeAIwD22WgF8QnAE78hudiyA","body":"(define (f x y . z) $\\langle \\textit{body} \\rangle$) "},{"body":"\n        the procedure ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"SCHEMEINLINE","body":"f"},{"body":" can be called with two or\n\tmore arguments. If we evaluate\n        ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"SNIPPET","latex":false,"id":27,"eval":true,"prependLength":0,"program":"chap=2&prgrm=NwAgygkgwgCiBMA6JBGAUGgFAMxChIAzCACwgCsIAbAJRA","body":"(f 1 2 3 4 5 6) "},{"body":"\n        then in the body of ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"SCHEMEINLINE","body":"f"},{"body":",\n\t","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"SCHEMEINLINE","body":"x"},{"body":" will be 1,\n\t","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"SCHEMEINLINE","body":"y"},{"body":" will be 2, and\n\t","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"SCHEMEINLINE","body":"z"},{"body":" will be the list\n\t","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"SCHEMEINLINE","body":"(3 4 5 6)"},{"body":". Given the definition\n        ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"SNIPPET","latex":false,"id":28,"eval":true,"prependLength":0,"program":"chap=2&prgrm=NwAgygkgwgCiBMA6JBGAUGgFAEwKYDMBLAO1xEwHMREQB3AShABIAdAGwENiK2yWAXXAA9+hfgG8ARgHtsATwC+IFgCcuPXE3pA","body":"(define (g . w) $\\langle \\textit{body} \\rangle$) "},{"body":"\n        the procedure ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"SCHEMEINLINE","body":"g"},{"body":" can be called with zero or\n\tmore arguments. If we evaluate\n        ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"SNIPPET","latex":false,"id":29,"eval":true,"prependLength":0,"program":"chap=2&prgrm=NwAgygkgwgCiBMA6JBGAUGgFAcxChIAzCACwgCsIAbAJRA","body":"(g 1 2 3 4 5 6) "},{"body":"\n        then in the body of ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"SCHEMEINLINE","body":"g"},{"body":",\n\t","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"SCHEMEINLINE","body":"w"},{"body":" will be the list\n\t","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"SCHEMEINLINE","body":"(1 2 3 4 5 6)"},{"body":".","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"FOOTNOTE_REF","id":"#footnote-link-4","body":"4","href":"/sicp/2.2.1#footnote-4"},{"body":"\n        Use this notation to write a procedure\n\t","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"SCHEMEINLINE","body":"same-parity"},{"body":" that takes one or more integers\n        and returns a list of all the arguments that have the same even-odd\n        parity as the first argument.  For example, \n        ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"SNIPPET","latex":false,"id":30,"eval":true,"prependLength":0,"program":"chap=2&prgrm=NwAgygkgwgCiBMA6JBGAUG4oDOBDAtgKYC0ADrgE4CWALgJ4g0D2IARoSAOZUBuhAdmwbYaAVwAmAmkA","body":";; same-parity to be given by student "},{"tag":"SNIPPET","latex":false,"id":31,"eval":true,"prependLength":3,"program":"chap=2&prgrm=NwAgygkgwgCiBMA6JBGAUG4oDOBDAtgKYC0ADrgE4CWALgJ4g0D2IARoSAOZUBuhAdmwbYaAVwAmAmhgAUeImUq0GKBCADMIACwgArCABsIAOwBKIA","body":"(same-parity 1 2 3 4 5 6 7) ","output":"(1 3 5 7)"},{"tag":"SNIPPET","latex":false,"id":32,"eval":true,"prependLength":3,"program":"chap=2&prgrm=NwAgygkgwgCiBMA6JBGAUG4oDOBDAtgKYC0ADrgE4CWALgJ4g0D2IARoSAOZUBuhAdmwbYaAVwAmAmhgAUeImUq0G8EAGYQAFhABWEADYQAdgCUQA","body":"(same-parity 2 3 4 5 6 7) ","output":"(2 4 6)"}]},{"tag":"SUBHEADING","id":"#h2","child":[{"body":"Mapping over lists","tag":"#text"}]},{"tag":"TEXT","id":"#p8","child":[{"body":"\n    One extremely useful operation is to apply some transformation to each\n    element in a list and generate the list of results. For instance, the\n    following\n    procedure\n    scales each number in a list by a given factor:\n    ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"SNIPPET","latex":false,"id":33,"eval":true,"prependLength":0,"program":"chap=2&prgrm=NwAgygkgwgCiBMA6JBGAUGgFAEwKYDMBLAO1xEwGcBjAQwBtcBaOwigFxELdwFsKR8NKmwD2AJwCUaEOUL5yxAK506Afk7c+UmTpDFCdabvJURxfpgBUJmmI28KEgUNGSjx45VoNmrDpipsOy4HJ0FhcQkoqSxqeiYWdnJEjhQEEABmEAAWEABWJxQABgkgA","body":"(define (scale-list items factor)\n  (if (null? items)\n      nil\n      (cons (* (car items) factor)\n            (scale-list (cdr items) factor)))) "},{"tag":"SNIPPET","latex":false,"id":34,"eval":true,"prependLength":0,"program":"chap=2&prgrm=NwAgygkgwgCiBMA6JBGAUGgFAZwMYEMAbAUwFpCBLbAFxE0ppBQRAGYQAWEAVgEomADLyA","body":"(scale-list (list 1 2 3 4 5) 10) ","output":"(10 20 30 40 50)"}]},{"tag":"TEXT","id":"#p9","child":[{"body":"\n    We can abstract this general idea and capture it as a common pattern\n    expressed as a higher-order\n    procedure,\n    just as in section ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"REF","body":"1.3","href":"/sicp/1.3"},{"body":".  The\n    higher-order\n    procedure\n    here is called ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"SCHEMEINLINE","body":"map"},{"body":".\n    ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"SCHEMEINLINE","body":"Map"},{"body":"\n    takes as arguments a\n    procedure\n    of one argument and a list, and returns a list of the results produced by\n    applying the\n    procedure\n    to each element in the list:","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"FOOTNOTE_REF","id":"#footnote-link-5","body":"5","href":"/sicp/2.2.1#footnote-5"},{"tag":"SNIPPET","latex":false,"id":35,"eval":true,"prependLength":6,"program":"chap=2&prgrm=NwAgygkgwgCiBMA6JBGAUGgFAEwKYDMBLAO1xEwEMAjAZxAA8BKNEcgYwHtjtzMA+BiAAMjBs1YSJmTAF5BI4eMlTMAHnmjMAWjGM9GHARJlMAWwoAHEBYBOHNiEIAXXKZpLMhfOWIBXADb+APyOLm5KksSE-izKmJzEdJi29uwUNqGu7hHKkmaW1nYO8dgZzll6lQbmVtRJ-oQ0TiBaKEIIiACsLSgoiABsICgA7HpAA","body":"(define (map proc items)\n  (if (null? items)\n      nil\n      (cons (proc (car items))\n            (map proc (cdr items))))) "},{"tag":"SNIPPET","latex":false,"id":36,"eval":true,"prependLength":12,"program":"chap=2&prgrm=NwAgygkgwgCiBMA6JBGAUGgFAEwKYDMBLAO1xEwEMAjAZxAA8BKNEcgYwHtjtzMA+BiAAMjBs1YSJmTAF5BI4eMlTMAHnmjMAWjGM9GHARJlMAWwoAHEBYBOHNiEIAXXKZpLMhfOWIBXADb+APyOLm5KksSE-izKmJzEdJi29uwUNqGu7hHKkmaW1nYO8dgZzll6lQbmVtRJ-oQ0TiBaKEIIiACsLSgoiABsICgA7HpAA","body":"(map abs (list -10 2.5 -11.6 17)) ","output":"(10 2.5 11.6 17)"},{"tag":"SNIPPET","latex":false,"id":37,"eval":true,"prependLength":7,"program":"chap=2&prgrm=NwAgygkgwgCiBMA6JBGAUGgFAEwKYDMBLAO1xEwFsBDABxBoCcB7AYxEIBdcKBnASjQhyhfOWIBXADaSA-Oy68BQ5SGKFJgleRZNiPco1baqDed35KtVyrXrM2mFtlOdzfd+4w26mSVQoARthU5AAefOQAVCChMZ5avoQ8HCAoCCAAzCAALO5AA","body":"(map (lambda (x) (* x x))\n     (list 1 2 3 4)) ","output":"(1 4 9 16)"},{"body":"\n    Now we can give a new definition of\n    ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"SCHEMEINLINE","body":"scale-list"},{"body":"\n    in terms of ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"SCHEMEINLINE","body":"map"},{"body":":\n    ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"SNIPPET","latex":false,"id":38,"eval":true,"prependLength":0,"program":"chap=2&prgrm=NwAgygkgwgCiBMA6JBGAUGgFAEwKYDMBLAO1xEwGcBjAQwBtcBaOwigFxELdwFsKR8NKmwD2AJwCUaEOR40ADuTo0eAI2w1yADwnkAVCC0ChoyVJkWZXXhQlSs1ekxbslrDigQgAzCAAsIACsuigADBJAA","body":"(define (scale-list items factor)\n  (map (lambda (x) (* x factor))\n       items)) "}]},{"tag":"TEXT","id":"#p10","child":[{"tag":"SCHEMEINLINE","body":"Map"},{"body":"\n    is an important construct, not only because it captures a common pattern,\n    but because it establishes a higher level of abstraction in dealing with\n    lists.  In the original definition of\n    ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"SCHEMEINLINE","body":"scale-list"},{"body":",\n    the recursive structure of the program draws attention to the\n    element-by-element processing of the list.  Defining\n    ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"SCHEMEINLINE","body":"scale-list"},{"body":"\n    in terms of ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"SCHEMEINLINE","body":"map"},{"body":" suppresses that level of\n    detail and emphasizes that scaling transforms a list of elements to a list\n    of results.  The difference between the two definitions is not that the\n    computer is performing a different process (it isn't) but that we\n    think about the process differently.  In effect,\n    ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"SCHEMEINLINE","body":"map"},{"body":" helps establish an abstraction barrier\n    that isolates the implementation of\n    procedures\n    that transform lists from the details of how the elements of the list are\n    extracted and combined.  Like the barriers shown in\n    \n\tfigure ,\n      \n    this abstraction gives us the flexibility to change the low-level details\n    of how sequences are implemented, while preserving the conceptual framework\n    of operations that transform sequences to sequences.\n    Section ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"REF","body":"2.2.3","href":"/sicp/2.2.3"},{"body":" expands\n    on this use of sequences as a framework for organizing programs.\n  ","tag":"#text"}]},{"tag":"EXERCISE","title":"Exercise 2.21","id":"#ex-2.21","child":[{"body":"\n    The\n    procedure","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"SCHEMEINLINE","body":"square-list"},{"body":"\n    takes a list of numbers as argument and returns a list of the squares of\n    those numbers.\n    ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"SNIPPET","latex":false,"id":39,"eval":true,"prependLength":0,"program":"chap=2&prgrm=NwAgygkgwgCiBMA6JBGAUG4oDOBHArgIYBOApgLQA2AltgC4h0D2IARqSAObUBupAdmwCeIevgAmAumgAUeImSq0GMmvRAoEIAMwgALAEoDQA","body":";; square-list to be given by student\n(square-list (list 1 2 3 4)) ","output":"(1 4 9 16)"},{"body":"\n    Here are two different definitions of\n    ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"SCHEMEINLINE","body":"square-list"},{"body":".\n    Complete both of them by filling in the missing expressions:\n    ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"SNIPPET","latex":true,"eval":false,"body":"\n(define (square-list items)\n  (if (null? items)\n      nil\n      (cons ?? ??)))\n      "},{"tag":"SNIPPET","latex":true,"eval":false,"body":"\n(define (square-list items)\n  (map ?? ??))\n      "}],"solution":[{"tag":"SNIPPET","latex":false,"id":40,"eval":false},{"tag":"SNIPPET","latex":false,"id":41,"eval":false}]},{"tag":"EXERCISE","title":"Exercise 2.22","id":"#ex-2.22","child":[{"body":" \n    Louis Reasoner tries to rewrite the first\n    ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"SCHEMEINLINE","body":"square-list"},{"body":"procedure\n    of exercise ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"REF","body":"2.21","href":"/sicp/2.2.1#ex-2.21"},{"body":" so that it evolves an\n    iterative process:\n    ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"SNIPPET","latex":false,"id":42,"eval":true,"prependLength":3,"program":"chap=2&prgrm=NwAgygkgwgCiBMA6JBGAUGgFAEwKYDMBLAO1xEwGcBHAVwEMAnMgDwEpyAqEZ711jHARJlKtRrgC0AG0IUALiEJzcAWwr8Q5PEVLkluBiDkALEgHMKIOsQoB3Axs1785YjSlSA-EdPELjpydrOwM0QMDMfUNMAGNsQxNzdRAw8LTNWIB7G3JqeiZyGMYfJL5U9Iqgm3sGPjKMqMVlNRBiQikytGBQPPFpWQU5TJAAIzIzQgA3XGJRgE8QeRo8YjksXqZ++XIZbZQEEABmEAAWPiA","body":"(define (square-list items)\n  (define (iter things answer)\n    (if (null? things)\n        answer\n        (iter (cdr things) \n              (cons (square (car things))\n                    answer))))\n  (iter items nil)) "},{"body":"\n    Unfortunately, defining\n    ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"SCHEMEINLINE","body":"square-list"},{"body":"\n    this way produces the answer list in the reverse order of the one desired.\n    Why?\n    ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"TEXT","id":"#p11","child":[{"body":"\n      Louis then tries to fix his bug by interchanging the arguments to\n    ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"SCHEMEINLINE","body":"cons"},{"body":":","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"SNIPPET","latex":false,"id":43,"eval":true,"prependLength":3,"program":"chap=2&prgrm=NwAgygkgwgCiBMA6JBGAUGgFAEwKYDMBLAO1xEwGcBHAVwEMAnMgDwEpyAqEZ711jHARJlKtRrgC0AG0IUALiEJzcAWwr8Q5PEVLkluBiDkALEgHMKIOsQoB3Axs1785YjSlSA-EdPELjpydrOwM0QMDMfUNMAGNsQxNzdTDw1M1YgHsbKxt7BhS0wqdReiZyGMYfJL4ax0jlQ301EGJCKT4MYFBqUskZeSMMkAAjMjNCADdcYhGATxB5GjxiOSwe8WlZBUx+hRQEEABmEAAWPiA","body":"(define (square-list items)\n  (define (iter things answer)\n    (if (null? things)\n        answer\n        (iter (cdr things)\n              (cons answer\n                    (square (car things))))))\n  (iter items nil)) "},{"body":"\n    This doesn't work either.  Explain.\n    ","tag":"#text"}]}],"solution":[{"tag":"OL","child":[{"tag":"LI","child":[{"body":"\n\t  The result list is reversed in the first program because the argument\n\t  list is traversed in the given order, from first to last, but squares\n\t  are added successively to the front of the answer list via\n\t  ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"SCHEMEINLINE","body":"cons"},{"body":".\n\t  The last element of the list is the last one to be added to the answer\n\t  and thus ends up as the first element of the result list.\n\t","tag":"#text"}]},{"tag":"LI","child":[{"body":"\n\t  The second program makes things worse! The result is not even a list\n\t  any longer, because the elements occupy the tail position of the\n\t  result list and not the head position.\n\t","tag":"#text"}]}]}]},{"tag":"EXERCISE","title":"Exercise 2.23","id":"#ex-2.23","child":[{"body":"\n    The\n    procedure","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"SCHEMEINLINE","body":"for-each"},{"body":"\n    is similar to ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"SCHEMEINLINE","body":"map"},{"body":".  It takes as arguments a\n    procedure\n    and a list of elements.  However, rather than forming a list of the\n    results,\n    ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"SCHEMEINLINE","body":"for-each"},{"body":"\n    just applies the\n    procedure\n    to each of the elements in turn, from left to right. The values returned by\n    applying the\n    procedure\n    to the elements are not used\n    at all—","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"SCHEMEINLINE","body":"for-each"},{"body":"\n    is used with\n    procedures\n    that perform an action, such as printing.  For example, \n    ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"SNIPPET","latex":false,"id":44,"eval":true,"prependLength":3,"program":"chap=2&prgrm=NwAgygkgwgCiBMA6JBGAUG4oBmB7ATgPoCmAhgMYAWIALriAEbEgDmAlgG7EB2jAniADONAK4ATHjQwAKPPgC0ZKiDQg10gDakAtgzGkQ0gB4BKQ92IB3DWwtnpYtoIAOWgaZOr1N4SACsAOwgAMzwKCAAHBEmJkA","body":"(for-each \n   (lambda (x) (newline) (display x))\n   (list 57 321 88)) ","output":"57\n321\n88"},{"body":"\n    The value returned by the call to\n    ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"SCHEMEINLINE","body":"for-each"},{"body":"\n    (not illustrated above) can be something arbitrary, such as true.  Give an\n    implementation of\n    ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"SCHEMEINLINE","body":"for-each"},{"body":".","tag":"#text"}],"solution":[{"tag":"SNIPPET","latex":false,"id":45,"eval":true,"prependLength":3,"program":"chap=2&prgrm=NwAgygkgwgCiBMA6JBGAUG4oBmB7ATgPoCmAhgMYAWIALriAEbEgDmAlgG7EB2jAniADONAK4ATHjQwYAFHnwBaMlRBoQ6mQBtSAWwZjSIGQA8AlEe7EA7praXzMsW0EAHbQLOm1G28JABWAHYQAGZ4FBAADkjTUyA","body":" "}]},{"tag":"DISPLAYFOOTNOTE","id":"#footnote-1","count":1,"href":"/sicp/2.2.1#footnote-link-1","child":[{"body":"In this book, we use ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"EM","child":[{"body":"list","tag":"#text"}]},{"body":" to mean a chain of\n    pairs terminated by the end-of-list marker.  In contrast, the term\n    ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"EM","child":[{"body":"list structure","tag":"#text"}]},{"body":" refers to any data structure made out of pairs, \n    not just to lists.","tag":"#text"}]},{"tag":"DISPLAYFOOTNOTE","id":"#footnote-2","count":2,"href":"/sicp/2.2.1#footnote-link-2","child":[{"body":"Since nested applications of\n    ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"SCHEMEINLINE","body":"car"},{"body":" and ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"SCHEMEINLINE","body":"cdr"},{"body":" are\n    cumbersome to write, Lisp dialects provide abbreviations for\n    them—for instance, \n    ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"SNIPPET","latex":true,"eval":false,"body":"\n(cadr $\\langle arg \\rangle$) = (car (cdr $\\langle arg \\rangle$))\n       "},{"body":"\n    The names of all such procedures start with ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"SCHEMEINLINE","body":"c"},{"body":"\n    and end with ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"SCHEMEINLINE","body":"r"},{"body":".  Each\n    ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"SCHEMEINLINE","body":"a"},{"body":" between them stands for a \n    ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"SCHEMEINLINE","body":"car"},{"body":" operation and each\n    ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"SCHEMEINLINE","body":"d"},{"body":" for a ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"SCHEMEINLINE","body":"cdr"},{"body":"\n    operation, to be applied in the same order in which they appear in the\n    name.  The names ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"SCHEMEINLINE","body":"car"},{"body":" and \n    ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"SCHEMEINLINE","body":"cdr"},{"body":" persist because simple combinations like\n    ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"SCHEMEINLINE","body":"cadr"},{"body":" are\n    pronounceable.","tag":"#text"}]},{"tag":"DISPLAYFOOTNOTE","id":"#footnote-3","count":3,"href":"/sicp/2.2.1#footnote-link-3","child":[{"body":"It's remarkable how much energy\n\tin the standardization of Lisp dialects has been dissipated in\n\targuments that are literally over nothing: Should\n\t","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"SCHEMEINLINE","body":"nil"},{"body":" be an ordinary name? Should the value\n\tof ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"SCHEMEINLINE","body":"nil"},{"body":" be a symbol?  Should it be a list?\n        Should it be a pair?  \n         \n        In Scheme, ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"SCHEMEINLINE","body":"nil"},{"body":" is an ordinary name, which\n\twe use in this section as a variable whose value is the end-of-list\n\tmarker (just as ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"SCHEMEINLINE","body":"true"},{"body":" is an ordinary\n\tvariable that has a true value).  Other dialects of Lisp, including\n\tCommon Lisp, treat ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"SCHEMEINLINE","body":"nil"},{"body":" as a special\n\tsymbol.  The\n        \n        authors of this book, who have endured too many language\n\tstandardization brawls, would like to avoid the entire issue.  Once we\n        have introduced quotation in\n\tsection ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"REF","body":"2.3","href":"/sicp/2.3"},{"body":", we will denote the\n\tempty list as ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"SCHEMEINLINE","body":"'()"},{"body":" and dispense with the\n        variable ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"SCHEMEINLINE","body":"nil"},{"body":" entirely.","tag":"#text"}]},{"tag":"DISPLAYFOOTNOTE","id":"#footnote-4","count":4,"href":"/sicp/2.2.1#footnote-link-4","child":[{"body":"To define\n\t","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"SCHEMEINLINE","body":"f"},{"body":" and ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"SCHEMEINLINE","body":"g"},{"body":" using\n        ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"SCHEMEINLINE","body":"lambda"},{"body":" we would write\n        ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"SNIPPET","latex":false,"id":46,"eval":false,"body":"(define f (lambda (x y . z) body))\n(define g (lambda w body))"}]},{"tag":"DISPLAYFOOTNOTE","id":"#footnote-5","count":5,"href":"/sicp/2.2.1#footnote-link-5","child":[{"body":"\t  \n    Scheme standardly provides a \n     ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"SCHEMEINLINE","body":"map"},{"body":"\n    procedure that is more general than the one described here. This more\n    general ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"SCHEMEINLINE","body":"map"},{"body":" takes a procedure of\n    ","tag":"#text"},{"body":"$n$","tag":"LATEX"},{"body":" arguments, together with\n    ","tag":"#text"},{"body":"$n$","tag":"LATEX"},{"body":" lists, and applies the procedure to all the\n    first elements of the lists, all the second elements of the lists, and so\n    on, returning a list of the results.  For example:\n    ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"SNIPPET","latex":false,"id":47,"eval":true,"prependLength":0,"program":"chap=2&prgrm=NwAgygkgwgCiBMA6JBGAUGgFAWwIYAcQBqETAGwEsBnAFxBQRAGYBKUy2kAFgAYQBWPgDYebctToB2HnwAcMkAE4ZLFkA","body":"(map + (list 1 2 3) (list 40 50 60) (list 700 800 900)) ","output":"(741 852 963)"},{"tag":"SNIPPET","latex":false,"id":48,"eval":true,"prependLength":0,"program":"chap=2&prgrm=NwAgygkgwgCiBMA6JBGAUGgFAWwIYAcRMAbXbAIwBNciAPEATwEoiBqEezAKgUaf7QghQkgEsAzgBcQKXgGYmg4UWITpAFhABWEADZ+QA","body":"(map (lambda (x y) (+ x (* 2 y)))\n     (list 1 2 3)\n     (list 4 5 6)) "}]}]